{{Infobox Aircraft accident |name = TACA Flight 390 |image = TACA Flight 390.jpg |caption = The wreckage of TACA Flight 390 |date = May 30, 2008 |type = Runway overrun, Pilot error |occurrence_type = Accident |site = [[Tegucigalpa, Honduras]] |fatalities = 5 (including 2 on the ground)<ref name="Diversions">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7429351.stm Honduras crash forces diversions]</ref> |Injuries = 65 |aircraft_type = [[Airbus A320-233]] |origin = [[El Salvador International Airport]] |plane1_stopover0 = [[Toncontin International Airport]] |plane1_stopover1 = [[Ramón Villeda Morales International Airport]] |destination = [[Miami International Airport]] |operator = [[TACA Airlines|Grupo TACA]] |tail_number = [http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20080530-0 EI-TAF] |passengers = 118 |crew = 6 |survivors = 121 |coords = {{coord|14.0702|-87.2141|region:HN_type:event|display=inline,title}} |}}
'''TACA Flight 390''' was a scheduled flight on May 30, 2008, by [[TACA Airlines]] from [[San Salvador]], [[El Salvador]], to [[Miami]], [[Florida]], [[United States]], with intermediate stops at [[Tegucigalpa]] and [[San Pedro Sula]] in [[Honduras]].<ref>[http://www.flightstats.com/go/FlightStatus/flightStatusByFlight.do?airline=(TA)+TACA&flightNumber=390&departureDate=2008-05-30&x=54&y=16 Flightstats for TA390 SAL-TGU-SAP-MIA] (May 30, 2008) {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929185110/http://www.flightstats.com/go/FlightStatus/flightStatusByFlight.do?airline=(TA)+TACA&flightNumber=390&departureDate=2008-05-30&x=54&y=16 |date=September 29, 2011 }}</ref> In this hull loss/fatalities accident, the [[Airbus A320 family|Airbus A320-233]] (registration EI-TAF, c/n 1374) overran the runway after landing at Tegucigalpa's [[Toncontín International Airport]] and rolled out into a street, crashing into an embankment and smashing several cars in the process.
==Passengers== The flight crew included [[El Salvador|Salvadorans]] Captain Cesare Edoardo D'Antonio Mena <!--Also written as César D'Antonio-->and First Officer Juan Rodolfo Artero Arevalo.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120326024743/http://www.aac.gob.sv/archivos/390/dantonio.pdf dantonio.pdf] ([https://www.webcitation.org Archive]) [[Civil Aviation Authority (El Salvador)|Civil Aviation Authority]] (El Salvador). Retrieved December 29, 2013.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120326024927/http://www.aac.gob.sv/archivos/390/artero.pdf artero.pdf] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6MEt3JexN?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20120326024927/http://www.aac.gob.sv/archivos/390/artero.pdf Archive]) Civil Aviation Authority (El Salvador). Retrieved December 29, 2013.</ref> All cabin crew members operating on the flight were [[Hondurans]]. The passengers consisted of:<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080918100258/http://news.taca.com/eng/nws/nwsbro.asp?key=902 TACA News] ([https://archive.is/20080918100258/http://news.taca.com/eng/nws/nwsbro.asp?key=902 Archive]) TACA Airlines (September 18, 2008). Retrieved December 29, 2013.</ref>
{|class="wikitable sortable" |- | '''Nationality''' || '''Passengers''' || '''Crew''' |- |{{HND}} || 60 || 5 |- |{{CRI}} || 9 || 0 |- |{{ARG}} || 8 || 0 |- |{{GUA}} || 7 || 0 |- |{{USA}} || 5 || 0 |- |{{NIC}} || 3 || 0 |- | {{SLV}} || 3 || 1 |- | {{MEX}} || 3 || 0 |- | {{BRA}} || 2 || 0 |- | {{CAN}} || 2 || 0 |- | {{COL}} || 2 || 0 |- | {{ESP}} || 1 || 0 |- | {{GEO}} || 1 || 0 |- | {{GER}} || 1 || 0 |- | {{ITA}} || 1 || 0 |- | {{URY}} || 1 || 0 |-class="sortbottom" |Total | 108 || 6 |}
A list of passengers was provided in the fifth press release on the crash from TACA Airlines. This list was in the Spanish and English sections.<ref>[http://news.taca.com/esp/nws/nwsbro.asp?key=897 Noticias GRUPO TACA BOLETÍN INFORMATIVO No. 5] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080602011953/http://news.taca.com/esp/nws/nwsbro.asp?key=897|date=June 2, 2008}}</ref>
Five people died as a result of the accident, including Captain D'Antonio. The deceased passengers were later confirmed as Jeanne Chantal Neele, wife of Brian Michael Fraser Neele ([[Brazil]]'s ambassador to Honduras), and Nicaraguan businessman [[Harry Brautigam]], president of the [[Central American Bank for Economic Integration]]; Brautigam died from a heart attack.<ref>[http://articles.cnn.com/2008-05-31/world/honduras.crash_1_runway-passengers-toncontin-international-airport?_s=PM:WORLD Five die as Honduras jet overshoots runway] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324130908/http://articles.cnn.com/2008-05-31/world/honduras.crash_1_runway-passengers-toncontin-international-airport?_s=PM:WORLD |date=2012-03-24 }}." ''[[CNN]]''.</ref> Ambassador Fraser Neele sustained injuries in the crash. The former head of the [[military of Honduras|Honduran armed forces]], General Daniel López Carballo, was also injured. There were two fatalities on the ground, one a taxi driver, in one of three vehicles crushed on the street by the aircraft. Mario Castillo, a survivor, said that the business class passengers sustained the most serious injuries.<ref name="Diversions"/>
==Investigation== Honduran authorities delegated the investigation of the accident to the [[Civil Aviation Authority (El Salvador)|Civil Aviation Authority]] of [[El Salvador]] as per the [[Convention on International Civil Aviation]].<ref>"[http://www.aac.gob.sv/archivos/cai/390.pdf Preliminary Report]." ([https://www.webcitation.org/5zhRi2VrA?url=http://www.aac.gob.sv/archivos/cai/390.pdf Archive]) Civil Aviation Authority (El Salvador). Retrieved June 9, 2009.</ref> The accident report stated that the airplane had landed with a 12-knot tailwind, 400 meters from the displaced approach end of the runway. Since this was the first intermediate stop on a long transcontinental flight, the aircraft was near its upper landing-weight limit (63.5t vs. 64.5t maximum allowable). In addition, the runway was wet, due to the passage of [[Tropical Storm Alma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20080530-0|title=Accident description, Friday 30 May 2008, TACA International Airlines, EI-TAF|work=ASN|accessdate=19 June 2014}}</ref>
